The number of Covid-19 active cases in the country stood at 21,480 as of Thursday. So far, from the 66,723 cases reported, 1,203 have died, with 44,040 patients recovering. The Health ministry announced that 919 more people had tested positive for the virus from a sample size of 6,135, representing a positivity rate of 14.9 per cent. All the new cases were Kenyans except 32. They comprised 559 males and 360 females aged between seven months and 87 years. On Thursday, Health CS Mutahi Kagwe announced that 23 more patients had passed away within 24 hours, while 414 more had recovered from the virus within the same period. From the recoveries, 316 were from the home-based care programme, with 98 having been discharged from health facilities. “A total of 1,279 patients are admitted in various health facilities countrywide, while 6,102 are in the home-based isolation and care. Sixty patients are in the intensive care unit, 20 of whom are on ventilator support and 35 on supplemental oxygen,” Kagwe said. “Another 89 patients are separately on supplemental oxygen, out of whom 71 are in the general wards and 18 in the high dependency units.” In terms of distribution per county, Nairobi continued to lead after recording 345 more cases, followed by Mombasa with 98, Nakuru with 76, Kilifi (74), Kiambu (44), Kericho with 41 and Trans Nzoia with 32. Kisumu recorded 31 more cases; Uasin Gishu 24; Kajiado 18; Nyeri 17; Kwale 14; Taita Taveta 13; Machakos 10; Siaya and Turkan nine cases each; Embu, Lamu and Meru with seven cases each, and West Pokot with six. Other counties that recorded new cases include Kisii, Murang’a, Narok and Marsabit with five cases each; Bomet and Homa Bay with three cases each; Laikipia, Kirinyaga and Nandi with two cases each; and Garissa, Nyandarua, Migori, Vihiga and Kakamega with one each. “To date, there are 2,207 healthcare workers who have tested positive for the virus — 1,106 are males and 1,101 females. Sadly, we have also lost 23 healthcare workers since the pandemic struck,” the CS said.